bug.short_desc: Build fails during pack normalization if bundle signed even though normalization should be skipped

long_desc.thetext:
In a recent test build, the build failed saying
[ERROR] Failed to execute goal org.eclipse.tycho.extras:tycho-pack200a-plugin:0.17.0:normalize (pack200-normalize) on project org.eclipse.jdt.core: Could not pack200 normalize jar file /opt/public/eclipse/builds/4I/gitCache/eclipse.platform.releng.aggregator/eclipse.jdt.core/org.eclipse.jdt.core/target/org.eclipse.jdt.core-3.9.0-SNAPSHOT.jar: pack200:normalize cannot be called for signed jar /opt/public/eclipse/builds/4I/gitCache/eclipse.platform.releng.aggregator/eclipse.jdt.core/org.eclipse.jdt.core/target/org.eclipse.jdt.core-3.9.0-SNAPSHOT.jar -> [Help 1]
If this is what I fear it is, it would be a real blocker. As you may know, we in Eclipse recently "turned on" the comparator, so that "old" bundles are taken from reference repo if qualifier is not changed.
So, I'm wondering if there is some path that if "old bundle" is already signed (as would often be true) that the build will fail.
Not sure why this would not show up "all the time", if true ... but, seems if something was already signed, and then we "asked" to pack:normalize it, that it would not be an ERROR ... at most a warning.
Perhaps it has to do with custom code in JDT core? But, thought I'd open this bug in Tycho first and would appreciate any insights or tips on debugging. I currently have "fail at end" turned on, so perhaps I should turn that off for next build to get a better idea of point of failure?
The complete (300M) log will temporarily be available at http://build.eclipse.org/eclipse/builds/mb4I.out.log.tempsave

In next test build, with "fail at end" turned off, it is pretty obvious is fails during jdt.core building. Not sure if they call "pack/normalize" themselves?
But, at least the log is only 200 M :)
http://build.eclipse.org/eclipse/builds/mb4I.out.log.tempsave2

It appears that its been decided jdt.core is deemed "same as in reference", and then it starts custom part, and then deems the "internal compiler" is different than reference (which, doesn't make any conceptual sense).
Thought I'd attach this relevant part of the log in case it makes it easier to get some expert help in solving the problem. I'm not sure if it takes a change in "Tycho"? Or, in jdt.core's custom code?

Adding Jay to CC since this might require a change in JDT's custom code. I didn't see any where we "turn on" packing, but might have to override what we inherit ... which would be ok since we don't sign the custom jar anyway ... but ... wasn't obvious to me where they would take place.

And I guess this need something like: jarprocessor.exclude.pack=true

What this means is the comparator 1. found a matching version in repo, for jdt.core (but they were slightly different, in signature only), but still used "old version" fro repo.

4. found a matching version of batch compiler (but, with lots of differences, for some reason).
I don't know how this helps us find a solution ... but ... thought it interesting.

Does your "custom code" copy things into META-INF of jdt.core (or its source?) Or, is it only the "batch compiler" that is "custom made"?

Just to give another data point, I've done several "test builds" today, without problem. But, it appears from git log that there were some changes to jdt.core. This "fits in" with the theory that if jdt.core changes (is not "replaced" by the one from the repo, via comparator) then things work, and perhaps it is only when jdt.core does not change that the problem manifests itself.
So, a "poor man's" work around might be to "touch" the bundle before each I-build. I'm not recommending that exactly, right now, just saying that if we see it fail again, probably any "touch" of the jdt.core in the Git repo will "solve" the problem.
But ... seems like there should be a better way.
If I'm reading the custom code right, its currently associated with the "package" phase ... which I assume by then, the "old" (unchanged) version of jdt.core has been decided and substituted. Is there any phase that we could specify that would be slightly earlier? After jdt.core built, but before comparator for it "runs"?

In other words, we are in a design hole ... Tycho/Maven assumes everything is done one-by-one, relatively independent of what comes before before/after.

I've decided I have been "barking up the wrong tree".
When my patch had no effect, I looked at error message closer,
Could not pack200 normalize jar file /opt/public/eclipse/builds/4I/gitCache/eclipse.platform.releng.aggregator/eclipse.jdt.core/org.eclipse.jdt.core/target/org.eclipse.jdt.core-3.9.0-SNAPSHOT.jar. And, looked at the jar closer.
Yes, it has already been signed, since it is "reusing" one, but why is it trying re-pack it?
The source has an eclipse.inf file, in both Git source, and in a built version (that is trying to be re-used), that says
jarprocessor.exclude.children=true jarprocessor.exclude.pack=true
And indeed, then a build is successful, there is no pack.gz file in our repo.
So, there's some different code path for "freshly built" jar ... and "re-used" jar?
So, seems clearly a bug in org.eclipse.tycho.extras:tycho-pack200a-plugin:0.17.0:normalize? Nothing to do with our "custom-plugin" code?

Created attachment 230419 patch to change "check if signed" condidtion to after decision to normalize
I think the attached patch shows a better place to check if the jar is already signed, and therefore can not be normalized ... it puts it after the other checks, that say the jar _should_ be normalized.
I suspect there are a couple of reasons this has not been seen before. 1) the baselineReplace functionality is relatively new, and we in Platform turned it "on" only a few weeks ago ... not sure if others have used it much. 2) Tycho/Maven normally does a great job of knowing what not to "reprocess" (such as it'd never send an Orbit prereq jar through this code path). 3) It may show up for this jdt.core case and not other cases, where the current artifact has been "replaced" from baseline, because jdt.core has some "custom plugin code" that may make the main jdt.core bundle appear "touched", though I'm pretty sure not. (Jay is on holiday this week, so may not be available to participate in discussion, but the code is at http://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.core.git/tree/org.eclipse.jdt.core/pom.xml#n28 if anyone wants to look. Pretty sure we just "copy from it", but maybe that makes it appear "changed" ... not sure how Tycho/maven decide that.
Even if we discovered this "custom bundle" case had more complications for the baselineReplace functionality, I think the attached patch is more conceptually correct and can avoid "false positives" -- as I think this case is.
